To determine whether (A × B) ∪ C = A × (B ∪ C) holds or not, we will first find the Cartesian products and unions involved in the equation and then compare the results.

Step 1: Find A × B and B ∪ C
A × B = {(a, b) | a ∈ A, b ∈ B} = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)}
B ∪ C = {2, 3} ∪ {3, 4} = {2, 3, 4}

Step 2: Find (A × B) ∪ C and A × (B ∪ C)
(A × B) ∪ C = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)} ∪ {3, 4} = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3), 3, 4}
A × (B ∪ C) = A × {2, 3, 4} = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

Step 3: Compare the results
(A × B) ∪ C = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3), 3, 4}
A × (B ∪ C) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

As we can see, (A × B) ∪ C ≠ A × (B ∪ C). The two sets are not equal, which means the Cartesian product of two sets is not associative with respect to union.
